If all they do is push the ball on the serve and it is not an offensive chop you should serve long with all 3 forms of spin. When you serve long with no spin and the serve is chopped it will come back with little to no backspin on it so it can easily be attacked. If you serve long with heavy backspin and the ball is pushed back then you can just attack it because there will not be that much spin on it (assuming the opponent cannot chop better than you). If you serve heavy side topspin then the ball has to chopped heavy and can no longer be pushed. If it is pushed then it would be an outright winner. You only serve short against medium to high level players (a pusher and blocker is not) because they will kill every long ball you give them. Hope this helps

On your forehand you are doing to much of a forward motion. When you get to high speeds you will struggle to control your shots due to the angle of your bat. You need more spin to land the ball on the table especially if you take the ball late. This is done by doing an upwards then forwards motion, instead of just a pure forward motion. You are also to rigid. You are supposed to be loose like a whip that snaps right at the end of the shot. Additionally your backhand is too flat. You need to drop the racket head and get more spin otherwise you will have trouble controlling you opponents spin. If you see the ball kick upwards, you know you have done a quality shot. Don't get me wrong your technique is pretty good but it could be even better. For reference watch this video of Hugo Calderano looping off the table and doing pure spin. Take note of how he drops the bat and then lifts it with heavy spin rather than hitting forward. You don't need to take it to this extreme level but it gives you a good idea on what to do.
